  "11-35": (
    caption: [Two types of active transport. (a) In primary active trans- port, the energy released by ATP hydrolysis drives solute (S1) movement against an electrochemical gradient. (b) In secondary active transport, a gradient of ion X (S1) (often Na(cid:2)) has been established by primary ac- tive transport. Movement of X (S1) down its electrochemical gradient now provides the energy to drive cotransport of a second solute (S2) against its electrochemical gradient.],
