  "11-38": (
    caption: [Role of the Na(cid:2)K(cid:2) ATPase in animal cells. This active transport system is primarily responsible for setting and maintaining the intracellular concentrations of Na(cid:2) and K(cid:2) in animal cells and for generating the membrane potential. It does this by moving three Na(cid:2) out of the cell for every two K(cid:2) it moves in. The electrical potential across the plasma membrane is central to electrical signaling in neurons, and the gradient of Na(cid:2) is used to drive the uphill cotransport of solutes in many cell types. c11BiologicalMembranesAndTransport.indd Page 413 13/09/12 11:42 AM user-F408 c11BiologicalMembranesAndTransport.indd Page 413 13/09/12 11:42 AM user-F408 /Users/user-F408/Desktop /Users/user-F408/Desktop (a)],
